"""
MKT Context Commentary — John chapters 9–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-john-9-10.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (contested terms)

Key decisions in this range:
- "the Evangelist" used consistently for the author (following chs 1–8 pattern)
- "the Jewish leaders" or "the leaders" for hoi Ioudaioi — the Jerusalem ruling class
- ἀποσυνάγωγος (9:22) treated as reflecting post-70 CE expulsion practice, possibly
  connected to the birkat ha-minim; historical debate noted
- Ezek 34 identified as primary background for the Shepherd discourse (ch. 10)
- "false shepherds of Israel" reading of ch. 10:8 limited to messianic pretenders, not
  OT figures generally — consistent with Josephus's accounts of revolutionary claimants
- Hanukkah / Feast of Dedication (10:22) given full historical treatment; Maccabean
  rededication language deliberately echoed by Jesus's "consecrated" claim (v.36)
- Ps 82 citation (10:34–35) treated via rabbinic qal wa-homer argument
- Mishnah Shabbat 7:2 and 14:4 cited for the Sabbath violations in 9:6, 14
- Josh 7:19 identified as background for "give glory to God" formula (9:24)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN = {
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>Blind beggars were a familiar fixture at city gates and temple precincts — pilgrimage sites concentrated the disabled, since charitable giving was considered a religious obligation and the foot traffic of worshippers made them the best economic location. The detail "blind from birth" is significant: it marks the condition as congenital and therefore beyond any natural remedy. The Evangelist places this encounter in the Jerusalem sequence following the Sukkot dispute of chapters 7–8, so the Temple Mount area is the most likely setting.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The disciples\' question reflects a widespread assumption in Second Temple Judaism: physical suffering, especially congenital deformity, was often read as punishment for sin (Exod 20:5; Deut 5:9 — visiting iniquity to the third and fourth generation). The possibility that a child could sin in the womb was actually debated in rabbinic literature (the tradition preserved in b. Yoma 82b; some argued prenatal sin was a category). The Pharisees\' later retort — "you were steeped in sin at birth" (v.34) — shows the view was alive and used as a social weapon. The question places Jesus within a live halakhic dispute about divine retribution and its causes.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Jesus\'s answer is neither philosophical nor systematic — it reframes the question rather than resolving it. The book of Job (particularly God\'s speeches in chs 38–42) had already established that automatic retribution theology was too simple; sufferers were not simply being punished. Rabbinic tradition wrestled with this, producing the category of <em>yissurin shel ahavah</em> — "afflictions of love," sufferings that refine rather than punish. Jesus\'s "so that the works of God might be displayed in him" borrows from the same logic: the man\'s condition has a purpose that transcends the sin-punishment grid.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The urgent day/night metaphor draws on a proverbial sense of limited working time. In agricultural Palestine, all outdoor labor was daylight-dependent; the phrase would have resonated immediately. But the Evangelist layers theological freight onto it: "the one who sent me" (<em>ton pempsanta me</em>) uses the same vocabulary as Siloam/"Sent" (v.7), placing Jesus\'s deeds within the Father\'s commissioned mission. The urgency is eschatological — the window of messianic opportunity does not remain indefinitely open.</p>',
    "5": '<p>This verse links directly to the Sukkot lamp-lighting ceremony that forms the backdrop of chapters 7–8. During Sukkot, four great golden menorot in the Court of Women were lit and said to illuminate all of Jerusalem (m. Sukkah 5:3). Against that setting, Jesus\'s "I am the light of the world" (also 8:12) sets up the symbolic logic of the healing: the one who claims to be the world\'s light now restores sight to a man who has never seen. The healing is not merely a kindness but a dramatized credential.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The therapeutic use of saliva in antiquity was well documented. Tacitus (Hist. 4.81) records the emperor Vespasian healing a blind man with spittle; Pliny the Elder (NH 28.7) lists its medicinal properties. This background explains the action without excusing it from a Sabbath perspective: applying saliva to the eyes on the Sabbath was explicitly forbidden (m. Shabb. 14:4 — one may not put saliva even on one\'s eye on the Sabbath). Beyond that, making clay by mixing saliva with earth constituted the act of "kneading" — one of the 39 prohibited categories of labor in m. Shabb. 7:2. Jesus performed two distinct violations before sending the man to wash. The detail is not incidental; the Evangelist foregrounds the Sabbath issue with "kneading" as the specific offense the Pharisees would have identified.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The Pool of Siloam (Heb. <em>Shiloah</em>) was fed by Hezekiah\'s tunnel from the Gihon spring, constructed ca. 701 BCE (2 Kgs 20:20; Isa 22:9–11). It lay in the lower city south of the Temple Mount and was used for ritual washing. Its Sukkot significance was central: each morning of the festival, priests descended to draw water from Siloam in a golden flask for the water-libation ceremony (<em>Simchat Beit HaShoevah</em>), pouring it on the altar to the sound of trumpets (m. Sukkah 4:9–10). The Evangelist\'s parenthetical gloss — "this word means Sent" — activates the name\'s meaning (<em>shaluach</em>, sent) in relation to Jesus\'s repeated self-description as the one "sent" by the Father. The blind man is sent to the pool of the Sent One. The washing and restoration mirrors a ritual immersion that effects actual change.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Beggars in the ancient world were recognized by their position more than by face — they occupied fixed locations as part of their survival strategy. The dispute among neighbors ("It is he" / "No, he only looks like him") reflects the genuine social disorientation caused by a radical change in the man\'s functional identity. He had been defined by what he could not do; he can now see. The cognitive difficulty of recognizing him is not mere literary device — it reflects the social category disruption that miracles produce.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The man\'s insistence "I am the man" (<em>Egō eimi</em> — the same construction John uses for Jesus\'s divine self-declarations) is likely coincidental here, but the verbal echo is notable. His simple first-person assertion against the skeptics\' doubt initiates the testimony pattern that will run through the entire chapter: direct personal witness against institutional denial.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The neighbors\' question "How were your eyes opened?" follows the natural investigative curiosity, but it also triggers the chain of testimony that the Evangelist has structured carefully. The question is asked three times in varying forms (vv.10, 15, 26) — a literary pattern that dramatizes the escalating interrogation and the man\'s increasingly confident response.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The man\'s account is bare and factual: a name, an action, a command, obedience, and result. He identifies Jesus as "the man they call Jesus" — the lowest possible christological category, a human being with a name. The progression of his confession (v.11: "the man Jesus"; v.17: "He is a prophet"; v.38: "Lord, I believe") is the chapter\'s spiritual arc, tracing a journey from sight to faith.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The man does not know where Jesus has gone — he obeyed the command to wash before meeting his healer. This detail underscores that his healing was not the result of a sustained relationship with Jesus but a one-directional act of command and compliance. The Evangelist notes it to establish the independence of the testimony: the man cannot have been coached by Jesus about what to say to the Pharisees.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"They brought him to the Pharisees" — the subject is the bystanders and neighbors from v.8. In Second Temple Jerusalem, the Pharisees exercised significant authority over Sabbath adjudication and the interpretation of Torah. Bringing a man who had allegedly been healed by a Sabbath-breaking act was a civic-religious act of community policing, not mere curiosity. The neighbors were fulfilling what they understood as their communal responsibility to report potential violations to recognized authorities.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The Evangelist now reveals the detail held back from the healing account: it was a Sabbath. This is the third Sabbath healing in John (5:9; 9:14), and the accumulated weight was deliberate. Under the Mishnaic classification, Jesus had performed at least two prohibited acts simultaneously (kneading the clay, applying saliva to eyes — m. Shabb. 7:2; 14:4). The standard halakhic principle was that medical intervention on the Sabbath was permitted only when life was threatened (<em>pikuach nefesh</em>); chronic blindness did not qualify. The Pharisees had legal grounds for their investigation.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Pharisees\' interrogation is a formal investigative process. Their question "How did you receive your sight?" is the standard opening of a halakhic inquiry — establishing the facts before determining whether a violation occurred. The man\'s abbreviated answer ("He put mud on my eyes, and I washed, and now I see") is pointedly brief; he has already told this story once. The terseness signals he is becoming aware of the bad faith of the process.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The division among the Pharisees reflects a genuine tension within halakhic reasoning. Deut 13:1–5 warns that a false prophet could perform signs — miraculous works were not automatically a credential. But many authorities held that authentic wonder-works testified to divine authorization unless disproven by doctrinal deviation. The Pharisees who argue "how can a sinner perform such signs?" are following one track; those who insist on the Sabbath violation are following another. The Evangelist does not present the Pharisees as a monolithic enemy but as a body capable of legitimate internal dispute — which makes the eventual expulsion more pointed.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"He is a prophet" — the healed man\'s first formal christological statement. In Second Temple Judaism, the categories of religious authority were roughly: scribe/teacher (authorized interpreter of Torah), prophet (bearer of a divine word), and messianic figure (the anointed deliverer). Calling Jesus a prophet acknowledged divine authorization without the full political weight of Messiahship. The woman of Samaria made the same identification (4:19) before reaching the Messiah conclusion. The Pharisees are asking the man for his opinion, placing his lay testimony in formal opposition to their institutional verdict.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The summoning of witnesses was standard in Jewish judicial procedure. Deut 17:6 required at least two witnesses for a capital case; Deut 19:15 generalized this to all charges. The leaders\' skepticism about whether the man had actually been blind ("They still did not believe") motivates the call for independent witness. The parents are the only people who can confirm both the congenital blindness and the present sight.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The three-part question — "Is this your son? Was he born blind? How is it that now he can see?" — corresponds to the three factual claims in dispute. Jewish legal procedure distinguished between facts requiring witness testimony and facts within personal knowledge; parents\' testimony about their son\'s birth condition falls in the latter category. The leaders are attempting to break the chain of testimony by attacking the least controllable link: the man\'s origin.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The parents\' confirmation of identity and birth condition is direct and unqualified — they have no reason to deny what they know to be true, and they cannot. Their evasion at the third point (how he now sees) is where the fear kicks in. Their answer "we know he is our son, and we know he was born blind" is notable for what it concedes: both facts are stipulated, undermining any argument that the healing never occurred.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"He is of age; he will speak for himself" — this is a legal formula. In Jewish law, a male reached majority at thirteen (bar mitzvah age), at which point he became legally responsible for his own testimony and ritual obligations. The Greek <em>hēlikian echei</em> ("he has the age") is a technical phrase indicating adult legal competence to testify on one\'s own behalf. The parents are deflecting to their son not merely out of cowardice but by invoking his legal standing as an adult witness.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The term <em>ἀποσυνάγωγος</em> ("put out of the synagogue") appears only in John\'s Gospel (here, 12:42, and 16:2) and signals a formal social sanction. The historical background is debated. By the late first century, a benediction against "heretics" (<em>birkat ha-minim</em>) had been inserted into the Amidah, the central prayer of the synagogue service — a benediction that Jewish followers of Jesus could not recite without condemning themselves. The exact dating and mechanism of formal exclusion is disputed (J. Martyn\'s influential reading sees ch. 9 as reflecting the Jamnia-era synagogue policy, ca. 85–90 CE), but the social reality the Evangelist describes was recognizable to his first-century audience: acknowledging Jesus as Messiah placed a person outside the covenantal community of the synagogue, with all the social, economic, and legal consequences that entailed.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The parents\' deflection — "He is of age; ask him" — is a repetition of v.21 that the Evangelist inserts to show the self-reinforcing nature of intimidation. They are not simply uninformed; they have calculated their social exposure and chosen self-preservation. Their silence is the sound of fear operating inside an institution.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Give glory to God by telling the truth" is a direct quotation of Joshua\'s words to Achan before his execution: "Give glory to the LORD God of Israel and give him the praise. Tell me what you have done; do not hide it from me" (Josh 7:19). The Pharisees are using a judicial oath formula — summoning the man to testify under formal religious obligation. The implicit message is: we know you have been lying; confess now before God. The presupposition is that the miracle did not happen as reported and that the man\'s testimony has been false.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The man\'s response is a masterpiece of forensic simplicity: he concedes what he does not know (the theological category of his healer) and asserts what he does know (his own sensory experience). In Jewish evidentiary tradition, direct personal testimony about one\'s own bodily experience was the strongest possible form of evidence — it required no corroboration and could not be refuted by counter-witness. "I was blind but now I see" is structurally irrefutable: whatever its theological implications, the empirical datum stands. The man has learned from his parents\' failure; he will not retreat from the one thing they cannot take away.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The repetition of "What did he do to you? How did he open your eyes?" is deliberate judicial badgering — an attempt to produce an inconsistency in repeated testimony. The Mishnah described how witnesses were cross-examined separately and repeatedly to detect discrepancies (m. Sanh. 4:1; 5:2). The tactic here is transparent: the Pharisees hope that if they ask enough times, the story will change. The man has recognized this and responds with irony rather than repetition.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The man\'s counter-offer — "Do you want to become his disciples too?" — is laced with sarcasm. The "too" is pointed: he is implying he himself is already a disciple, a claim he has not explicitly made. More importantly, he exposes the bad faith of the inquiry: a genuine investigation seeks information; a predetermined verdict seeks compliance. His question to his interrogators — would they like to join? — inverts the power dynamic of the hearing in a way that is socially daring for a man of his status.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"We are disciples of Moses" — this is the Pharisees\' central self-identification and the source of their authority claim. The Mishnah traces the chain of Torah transmission from Moses through Joshua, the elders, the prophets, and the men of the Great Assembly (m. Avot 1:1); the Pharisees understood themselves as the authorized inheritors of this tradition. To be a disciple of Moses was to stand within the living stream of covenant interpretation. The contrast — "you are this fellow\'s disciple!" — was designed to place the man outside that stream, in the company of an unauthorized teacher whose credentials they reject.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"We don\'t know where he comes from" — knowing a teacher\'s lineage, training, and ordination chain was essential in Jewish tradition for assessing his authority. Rabbinic authority was transmitted through a recognized line: a student studied under an acknowledged master and received a form of authorization (<em>semikha</em>). Jesus had no known teacher, no recognized school, and no institutional backing. From the Pharisaic perspective, his unverifiable origin was a disqualification. The Evangelist notes the irony: they "know" Moses (whose divine origin they accept on faith) but refuse to credit testimony about Jesus whose works are in front of them.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The man\'s observation — "Now that is remarkable! You don\'t know where he comes from, yet he opened my eyes" — applies the standard Pharisaic logic back against them. The opening of eyes of one born blind was not a routine healing; it was categorically unprecedented, which was precisely its significance. Isaiah 29:18 and 35:5 associated the recovery of sight for the blind with the era of divine intervention; 42:7 extends this to the servant\'s mission. An audience steeped in prophetic literature should have recognized the eschatological weight of what had happened. The man is pointing out the logical collapse: the greater the work, the stronger the inference about its source.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The principle the man invokes — "God does not listen to sinners; He listens to the godly person who does his will" — is grounded in Ps 66:18 ("If I had cherished sin in my heart, the Lord would not have listened") and echoed in Prov 15:29 and 28:9. It was a widely accepted axiom. The man is not making a novel theological claim but deploying shared premises — the same premises the Pharisees would invoke — to reach the conclusion they reject. His argument is internally consistent within the Pharisaic framework.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"Nobody has ever heard of opening the eyes of a man born blind" — this is precisely the point the Evangelist wants the reader to notice. The unprecedented nature of the healing corresponds exactly to the prophetic texts (Isa 29:18; 35:5; 42:7) that associated restoration of sight with the messianic age. A healing that had never occurred in all of Israel\'s history, occurring now, should trigger recognition of what age this is. The man who was born blind is, ironically, the one who sees this most clearly.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The man\'s logical conclusion — "If this man were not from God, he could do nothing" — echoes the language Nicodemus used (3:2: "no one could perform the signs you are doing if God were not with him") and the Pharisees\' own debate (v.16). He is applying the most favorable Pharisaic criterion for divine authorization (authentic works = divine backing) to its logical conclusion. The argument is unassailable within their own framework; the only recourse is to attack the witness rather than the evidence.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"You were steeped in sin at birth; how dare you lecture us!" — the Pharisees deploy against the man the very premise his disciples articulated in v.2: congenital blindness = sin at birth. Having failed to discredit his testimony, they use his disability history as grounds to dismiss his theological competence entirely. This is a rhetorical strategy of ad hominem disqualification: you have no authority to teach because of what you were born into. The expulsion (<em>exebalon auton exō</em>) is a formal judicial act — the same verb appears in 2:15 for Jesus driving out the money-changers. The man who received physical sight is now cast into social darkness by those who claim to see.</p>',
    "35": '<p>Jesus\' act of seeking out the expelled man is pastorally pointed. He had not been present for the interrogation; he "heard that they had thrown him out." The seeking and finding (v.35) inverts the usual pilgrimage dynamic — the worshipper comes to Jerusalem seeking God, but here the expelled outsider is found by the one he had not yet fully identified. "Son of Man" is the Danielic figure of 7:13–14 — the heavenly vindicator who receives authority from the Ancient of Days — carrying not just eschatological authority but the specific connotation of one who vindicates the righteous against unjust judgment.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"Who is he, sir? Tell me so that I may believe in him" — the man\'s question shows he is in the same position as the Samaritan woman in 4:25 ("When the Messiah comes, he will explain everything to us"). He is functionally ready to believe; he lacks only identification. His willingness to believe in a figure he cannot yet fully see parallels the faith he showed in obeying the command to wash before he had met his healer face to face.</p>',
    "37": '<p>Jesus\'s self-disclosure — "You have now seen him; in fact, he is the one speaking with you" — echoes the pattern of the Samaritan woman encounter (4:26: "I, the one speaking to you — I am he") and the disciples\' recognition of the risen Jesus. The "you have now seen him" is laden with irony: the man who was blind has now literally seen the Son of Man, while those who could see remain in darkness. The Evangelist has constructed the narrative so that the healing of physical sight is structurally inseparable from the gift of spiritual recognition.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"Lord, I believe" followed immediately by <em>prosekunēsen autō</em> — he "worshiped him." The verb <em>proskuneō</em> in the Fourth Gospel is the act appropriate to deity (4:20–24: the Samaritan worship discussion; 12:20: Greeks come to worship at Passover). The man\'s act is not merely respectful deference but the posture of one who recognizes divine presence. In contrast, the Pharisees had demanded that he "give glory to God" — and he does, but to God embodied before him. The irony is fully visible to the reader.</p>',
    "39": '<p>Jesus\'s statement — "For judgment I have come into this world, so that the blind will see and those who see will become blind" — echoes the reversal language of Isa 6:9–10 (blinding as divine judgment on those who refuse to see, cited by all four Gospels as fulfilled in the response to Jesus\'s ministry) and Isa 42:18–19 (the irony of the blind servant who is sent to open blind eyes). The paradox is judicial: the arrival of light creates darkness for those who insist on their own vision and refuse the offered sight. The Evangelist has structured the entire chapter as a dramatization of this principle.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The Pharisees\' question — "Are we blind too?" — assumes a negative answer. They are the sighted ones; the recently-healed beggar is the historical blind man. Their question is rhetorical. But the Evangelist places it at this exact point so that Jesus\'s answer lands as a verdict rather than a response.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The closing verdict uses the logic of legal culpability. In the ancient Near Eastern and Jewish legal world, guilt required knowledge: one who acted in ignorance was treated differently from one who acted knowingly (Lev 4:2–3; Num 15:28–30 — unintentional sin vs. high-handed sin). Jesus does not say blindness itself is sin; he says that claiming sight while refusing to see removes the legal defense of ignorance. The Pharisees have seen the evidence, heard the testimony, and rejected it — their guilt is therefore deliberate. The chapter ends on this forensic note, perfectly prepared for the Shepherd discourse that follows in chapter 10, addressed to the same audience.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>The Shepherd discourse is addressed directly to the Pharisees who expelled the blind man — v.9:40 ("some Pharisees who were with him heard him say this") provides the immediate audience. There is no scene break; the discourse follows the verdict of 9:41. Palestinian sheep pen management in the first century: sheep were typically kept at night in a shared stone enclosure (an <em>aulē</em>, a walled courtyard) serving multiple village flocks. The single entrance (gate, <em>thura</em>) was watched by a gatekeeper. Thieves would vault the wall rather than use the gate. The image was immediately legible to a rural Palestinian audience — and the Pharisees, as Jerusalem urbanites who administered the temple apparatus, would have understood that the discourse was about them.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The shepherd enters "by the gate" — the authorized entrance. In contrast to the thief who bypasses the gate, the legitimate shepherd uses the established access point. The gate/gatekeeper structure reflects actual village architecture: a shared pen with one monitored entrance ensured that only authorized herders could withdraw their flocks. The parable addresses authority — who has legitimate access to God\'s people — rather than mere pastoral care.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The shepherd calls "his own sheep by name" — individual naming of animals was standard practice in ancient pastoralism; sheep were long-term investments, not anonymous livestock. The ability of sheep to distinguish their own shepherd\'s voice from strangers\' was noted in ancient accounts (Theophrastus and later writers). The morning departure from a shared pen was a recognizable daily event: the shepherd would arrive, call his own sheep from among the mixed flock, and lead them out before other shepherds arrived. "Leads them out" (<em>ekballei</em>) is the same verb used for the expulsion of the blind man (9:34) — the Shepherd leads out those whom the false authorities cast out.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The shepherd "goes on ahead" — a distinctively Palestinian practice; Greek and Roman shepherds often drove their flocks from behind. Leading from the front was characteristic of Palestinian herding, where the shepherd scouted the path and the sheep followed his familiar voice. The difference was noted by ancient travelers in the region. The model of leadership implicit here is relational and directional: the shepherd does not manage the sheep from a distance but walks ahead into the unknown, and the sheep follow because they know his voice.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The flight from a stranger\'s voice reflects an observable fact about sheep behavior (noted by ancient authors), but also carries deliberate typological weight. The Pharisees who have just expelled the blind man are the "strangers" whose voice Jesus\'s sheep will not follow. The man born blind had demonstrated this already: when the institutional authorities demanded that he deny what he knew to be true, he refused. He followed the voice he had learned to trust and fled from those whose version of reality he did not recognize.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Greek <em>paroimia</em> — translated as "figure of speech" — is the Johannine equivalent of the Synoptic <em>parabole</em> (the Evangelist uses <em>paroimia</em> rather than <em>parabole</em> throughout the Gospel). The Pharisees\' failure to understand is a continuation of the blindness motif established throughout chapter 9. Those who claim to see cannot perceive what is plain to those who have received sight. The Evangelist uses the misunderstanding as a narrative device that both characterizes the audience and explains why Jesus continues the discourse with explicit interpretation.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"I am the gate for the sheep" — the functional identification of the shepherd with the gate reflects actual pastoral practice: at night, when the shepherd himself slept in the gateway of the pen, his body literally became the barrier between the flock and the outside. He was the gate. Beyond this physical detail, the claim to be the gate through which access to the flock is mediated is a claim to replace the institutional gatekeeping function that the Pharisees had exercised — demonstrated most recently in their judicial control over who was permitted to remain within the synagogue community (9:22).</p>',
    "8": '<p>"All who have come before me are thieves and robbers" does not condemn OT figures (Moses, the prophets, the kings) — the sheep "have not listened to them" is the distinguishing criterion, and Israel did listen to Moses and the prophets. The Evangelist almost certainly refers to the messianic pretenders and revolutionary figures who arose in the decades before Jesus. Josephus documents a series of claimants who gathered followings by promising liberation: Theudas (Acts 5:36; Ant. 20.5.1), the Egyptian prophet who led four thousand into the wilderness (Acts 21:38; Ant. 20.8.6), unnamed figures in the Felix period (Ant. 20.8.5). These men "climbed in by some other way" — they bypassed legitimate covenantal credentials and exploited the messianic hopes of the people for their own ends.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Whoever enters through me will be saved. They will come in and go out, and find pasture" — "coming in and going out" is a standard OT formula for military-pastoral leadership. Moses uses it in Num 27:17, praying for a successor "so that the LORD\'s people will not be like sheep without a shepherd"; it appears in Deut 31:2 for Moses\'s own leadership and in 1 Sam 18:13 for David\'s. The phrase describes the full scope of a leader\'s activity: entrance into relationship with God\'s people, movement with them, and provision of what they need. The "pasture" (<em>nomē</em>) is covenant abundance — sustenance within the sphere of God\'s care.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The contrast between the thief\'s purpose (steal, kill, destroy) and Jesus\'s purpose (life in abundance) echoes the Ezekiel 34 indictment of Israel\'s shepherds: "You eat the curds, clothe yourselves with the wool and slaughter the choice animals, but you do not take care of the flock" (Ezek 34:3). The hired shepherds exploit; the true shepherd gives. The phrase "life to the full" (<em>zōē... perisson</em>) — life more than enough — is the contrast to a bare subsistence theology in which God manages risk but provides no more than survival.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The Ezekiel 34 background is structurally central to the Shepherd discourse. God\'s oracle against Israel\'s corrupt shepherds ends with the promise: "I myself will search for my sheep and look after them... I myself will tend my sheep and have them lie down... I will search for the lost and bring back the strays" (Ezek 34:11–16). The "I myself" is emphatic in Hebrew — God will personally do what the human shepherds failed to do. The Evangelist presents Jesus as the fulfillment of this divine pledge. "The good shepherd" (<em>ho poimēn ho kalos</em>) — <em>kalos</em> carries both moral goodness and aesthetic excellence, the right and noble shepherd, not merely a competent one.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The hired hand (<em>misthōtos</em>) occupied a specific and generally low-status position in ancient Palestinian agriculture. Mishnaic discussions of hired shepherd liability are extensive (b. B.M. 93a–b): a hired shepherd\'s contractual obligations and exposure to loss differed from the owner\'s. Under some rulings, a hired hand who abandoned the flock during a wolf attack bore no legal liability (force majeure), but the moral verdict of abandonment was clear. The contrast the Evangelist draws is between self-interest and identification with the flock: the hired hand\'s loyalty is to his wage, not to the sheep.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"He is a hired hand and cares nothing for the sheep" — the language of "caring" (<em>melei autō</em>) describes the commitment of ownership and relationship. An owner who loses a sheep has lost his own property and possibly his livelihood; a hired hand has merely lost someone else\'s animal. The institutional equivalent is the difference between a leader whose authority comes from genuine service to the community and one whose position is maintained for the sake of the benefits it provides. The Pharisees\' expulsion of the blind man is the concrete instance: they "cared nothing" for the man\'s welfare once he became a liability.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The mutual knowledge of shepherd and sheep uses the verb <em>ginōskō</em> in a way that echoes the Hebrew <em>yāda\'</em> — knowing as relational, experiential, and covenantal rather than merely informational. God\'s covenant "knowing" of Israel (Amos 3:2: "You only have I known of all the families of the earth"; Hos 13:4–5: "I have been the LORD your God ever since Egypt; you shall acknowledge no God but me, no Savior except me") is the background. The shepherd knows each sheep; each sheep recognizes the shepherd. The relationship is not generic but particular.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The parallel "as the Father knows me and I know the Father" escalates the shepherd-sheep relationship to the Father-Son level. The same <em>yāda\'</em> dynamic — intimate, covenantal, mutual knowing — is claimed at the divine level. This places the pastoral relationship within the inner life of God: the shepherd\'s care for his sheep is not analogical to divine love but participates in it. The addition "I lay down my life for the sheep" anchors the theological claim in a concrete historical act.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Other sheep that are not of this sheep pen" — universally interpreted as Gentiles, those outside the covenant people of Israel. The promise of "one flock and one shepherd" echoes Ezek 37:24 (the vision of restored Israel: "My servant David will be king over them, and they will all have one shepherd") and Isa 56:6–8 (the inclusion of foreigners who bind themselves to the LORD: "I will bring them to my holy mountain... for my house will be called a house of prayer for all nations"). The single shepherd does not abolish Israel\'s particularity but fulfills the covenant promise to include the nations within its scope (Gen 12:3; Isa 49:6).</p>',
    "17": '<p>"The reason my Father loves me is that I lay down my life — only to take it up again" — the conditional clause is not "if" but "because" (<em>hoti</em>): the Father\'s love is given as the ground of the self-offering, not its reward. The theological logic is surprising: the Father does not love the Son despite the cross but in the very act of it. The voluntary character of the death ("I lay it down of my own accord," v.18) was a critical apologetic point in early Christian proclamation — crucifixion was a shameful death imposed by enemies; Jesus reframes it as a deliberate act of covenant faithfulness.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The claim to "authority to lay down my life and authority to take it up again" is without precedent in Jewish tradition. Moses, Elijah, and Elisha raised the dead by divine power mediated through prayer; they did not claim personal authority over their own life and death. The language of authority (<em>exousia</em>) over death invokes divine prerogative. Deut 32:39 attributes this exclusively to YHWH: "I put to death and I bring to life." The phrase "this command I received from my Father" grounds the extraordinary claim in covenantal obedience: the authority is real but derivative, exercised within the Father\'s will.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The division (<em>schisma</em>) is the third occurrence of this pattern in John (7:43; 9:16; 10:19) — each following a significant Jesus action or teaching. Division is the social cost of a decisive claim: it ruptures the existing consensus. The Evangelist uses <em>schisma</em> technically, in a context where the word had legal-institutional connotations (a formal split or dispute requiring adjudication).</p>',
    "20": '<p>The accusation of demon possession (<em>daimonion echei kai mainetai</em> — "he has a demon and is raving mad") was a recognized category for dismissing a religious claimant whose credentials were rejected. In the Synoptic tradition, the Pharisees attributed Jesus\'s exorcisms to Beelzebul (Matt 12:24; Mark 3:22); here the accusation is generalized to his teaching. The effect is to pathologize dissent: the claim is not wrong in theory but the speaker is unhinged, so his words should not be evaluated on their merits.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Can a demon open the eyes of the blind?" — the counter-argument refers directly back to chapter 9. The sign has not been forgotten; it continues to function as evidence that the demonic-dismissal response is inadequate. The rhetorical logic is: a demon\'s characteristic activity is destruction, not restoration; therefore the healer of the blind man does not fit the demonic category. The counter-argument keeps the evidence before the audience and refuses to let the prior sign be absorbed into the accusation.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The Feast of Dedication (<em>Enkainia</em>) is Hanukkah — the eight-day festival instituted in 164 BCE by Judas Maccabaeus after the recapture and rededication of the Jerusalem Temple, which Antiochus IV Epiphanes had desecrated with the "abomination of desolation" (1 Macc 4:36–59; 2 Macc 10:1–8). The festival celebrated both military liberation and the restoration of proper worship, and was observed with the lighting of menorot and public rejoicing. Its name, <em>enkainia</em>, means "rededication" or "renewal" — the same root as the verb "consecrated" in v.36. The festival was mid-winter (Kislev = November–December), explaining why Jesus was walking in a sheltered portico rather than the open courts.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Solomon\'s Colonnade (also called Solomon\'s Porch) was the eastern portico along the Kidron Valley side of the Temple Mount. According to Josephus (Ant. 20.9.7; War 5.5.1), it was believed to be the sole surviving remnant of Solomon\'s original Temple, preserved through all the destructions and rebuildings. This is the same location where the early church gathered after Pentecost (Acts 3:11; 5:12) — a public, sheltered space associated with both Solomonic legacy and communal assembly. Meeting there during Hanukkah, a festival celebrating the Maccabean restoration of the temple, carries heavy irony: the one who is greater than the Temple (2:21) walks in its oldest preserved colonnade.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The demand "Tell us plainly" (<em>parrēsia hēmin eipe</em> — speak to us in clear speech, openly) reflects both frustration and political calculation. A public, unambiguous Messianic claim had revolutionary implications under Roman occupation — it amounted to a claim to kingship. The Jewish leaders\' demand may have been a trap: an affirmative answer could be reported to Rome as sedition (cf. 19:12). The Hanukkah context adds irony: the festival celebrated king-priests who rededicated the temple and defeated a pagan empire. A Messianic declaration there would activate the full Maccabean political register.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Jesus\'s appeal to "the works I do in my Father\'s name" as testimony reflects the Deuteronomic criterion for prophetic authentication (Deut 13:1–5; 18:21–22): what a prophet speaks must come true, and works done in the LORD\'s name demonstrate divine authorization. The Evangelist has constructed the narrative so that Jesus\'s works — healing at pools, multiplying loaves, raising the dead — are the continuous evidence-base that his opponents are obliged to reckon with. The appeal is not circular; it is evidentiary.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"You do not believe because you are not my sheep" — this inverts the conventional religious epistemology of the period. Normally, one saw a sign, evaluated it, and then believed or disbelieved on the basis of the evidence. Here, the capacity to recognize the sign is itself dependent on a prior relational condition — being one of the shepherd\'s sheep. The Evangelist\'s point is not predestinarian in the sense of excluding human response, but relational: belonging to the flock precedes recognizing the shepherd\'s voice, not the other way around.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"My sheep listen to my voice; I know them, and they follow me" — the three verbs (listen, know, follow) describe the full relational arc of discipleship. The blind man of chapter 9 enacted all three: he heard Jesus\'s command, Jesus knew him (sought him out after the expulsion), and he followed by worshipping. The Evangelist has arranged the chapters so that the Shepherd discourse interprets the preceding narrative, and the healed man is the dramatic illustration of what "my sheep" means.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"No one will snatch them out of my hand" — the imagery of the divine hand from which nothing can be taken draws on Deut 32:39 ("No one can deliver out of my hand") and Isa 43:13 ("No one can deliver out of my hand"). These texts apply to YHWH\'s sovereign power over life and death. The Evangelist places this language in Jesus\'s mouth as a statement of his own authority, preparing for the explicit unity claim of v.30. The promise of "eternal life" in this context is covenant language — not merely immortality but the unbreakable life of the age to come, sustained by the shepherd\'s care.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"My Father, who has given them to me, is greater than all" — the "greater than all" echoes the divine incomparability formula of the OT (Exod 18:11; Ps 95:3; 96:4). The point is not that the Father is greater than the Son in the trinitarian sense (a later theological debate) but that the Father\'s sovereign power over all things is the ultimate security of the sheep. The double protection — "no one can snatch them out of my Father\'s hand" — establishes that Jesus\'s hand and the Father\'s hand are functionally equivalent in their protective power, setting up v.30.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"I and the Father are one" — <em>hen esmen</em>, "one" is neuter in Greek: unity of nature or action, not numerical identity ("one person"). The Hanukkah setting is deliberately ironic: the festival celebrated the rededication of the Temple as the dwelling of God\'s presence. Jesus now claims a unity with the Father that supersedes the Temple\'s function as the locus of divine presence. The statement was heard as a blasphemy claim (v.31: immediate move to stone him), which confirms that the audience understood it as a divine-nature claim, not merely a claim of moral alignment with God\'s will.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Stoning was the prescribed punishment for blasphemy under Lev 24:16 ("Anyone who blasphemes the name of the LORD is to be put to death. The entire assembly must stone them"). This is the second stoning attempt in John (8:59). The act is extrajudicial — no formal trial has occurred — reflecting the ancient provision for spontaneous community action in cases of flagrant public blasphemy. The leaders are not framing a legal case at this point; they are responding to what they have heard as a public profanation that demands immediate action.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"I have shown you many good works from the Father. For which of these do you stone me?" — the appeal to works interrupts the extrajudicial process by demanding that the accusers specify their charge. The works function as public evidence that cannot be denied; the question is why the response to undeniable goods is violence. The Evangelist uses this moment to clarify that the conflict is not about competence or results but about the identity claim embedded in the works.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"You, a mere man, claim to be God" — the charge of blasphemy is now explicit. In Second Temple Jewish legal thinking, blasphemy included arrogating divine prerogatives, making oneself equal to God, or claiming to act in God\'s name without authorization. The leaders\' formulation — "a mere man" (<em>anthrōpos ōn</em>, being human) — states the problem precisely: the offense is the disproportionate claim, a human being claiming divine status. The irony the Evangelist has been building throughout the Gospel is that the charge is simultaneously legally accurate from the accusers\' frame and theologically false from the Evangelist\'s frame.</p>',
    "34": '<p>Jesus quotes Ps 82:6 — "I said, \'You are gods; you are all sons of the Most High.\'" The psalm addresses corrupt human judges who failed to administer justice; the "gods" (Heb. <em>elohim</em>) are human authorities. In rabbinic tradition, this verse was interpreted in two main ways: (1) it refers to Israel at Sinai, who received the Torah and were thereby elevated to angelic/divine status, only to fall back when they worshipped the golden calf; (2) it refers to judges generally, whose authority to render binding legal decisions constitutes a form of delegated divine power. Either reading establishes that Scripture uses divine language for human recipients of God\'s word without blasphemy.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The parenthetical note — "and Scripture cannot be set aside" (<em>ou dunatai luthēnai hē graphē</em>) — is a technical halakhic principle: a scriptural text, once established as canonical, cannot be abrogated or dismissed. The Evangelist places this legal principle in Jesus\'s argument as an axiom that the Pharisees themselves accept. The argument form is <em>qal wa-homer</em> (from lesser to greater): if the minor case (human judges called "gods") is permitted by Scripture, the major case (the one the Father consecrated and sent into the world) is certainly permissible. The word "consecrated" (<em>hēgiasen</em>) picks up the Hanukkah vocabulary: the festival\'s rededication (<em>enkainia</em>) shares its semantic field with consecration.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"The one whom the Father set apart as his very own and sent into the world" — "set apart" (<em>hēgiasen</em>, consecrated, sanctified) uses the same root as the Hanukkah festival name (<em>enkainia</em>) and the priestly consecration vocabulary of the LXX. The deliberate verbal echo suggests that Jesus is contrasting the Maccabean rededication of a physical building with his own consecration as the Father\'s sent one. The Temple was rededicated; Jesus was consecrated. The festival celebrates a rededicated building; the Evangelist presents the one who replaces the temple (2:21) as the true fulfillment of the dedication theme.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"Do not believe me unless I do the works of my Father" — the appeal to works as the epistemological warrant returns one final time. The Evangelist has built the entire Farewell Discourse section on this principle: the works, not the words alone, are the grounds of recognition. The offer is epistemically modest: Jesus does not ask for belief in abstract claims; he points to observable evidence. The argument is falsifiable, which is what makes the leaders\' rejection culpable rather than merely mistaken.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"That the Father is in me, and I in the Father" — the mutual indwelling language of the Farewell Discourses (14:10–11; 17:21–23) appears here for the first time. It is relational and dynamic rather than spatial: the Father\'s activity is expressed through the Son\'s works, and the Son\'s identity is constituted by his relationship with the Father. The argument moves from external works (observable) to internal relationship (theological), using the former as evidence for the latter.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"Again they tried to seize him, but he escaped their grasp" — the failed arrest echoes 7:30 and 8:20, both of which the Evangelist explained with "his hour had not yet come." The same principle operates here implicitly: Jesus acts and speaks on his own timing, not the authorities\'. The Hanukkah confrontation ends without the crisis the leaders sought; the timing of the Passover arrest is governed by a different calendar.</p>',
    "40": '<p>"Across the Jordan to where John had been baptizing in the early days" — the Evangelist returns Jesus to Bethany beyond the Jordan (1:28), the geographic origin of the ministry. The retreat from Jerusalem to Transjordan places Jesus outside the immediate judicial reach of the Jerusalem authorities and within a region more hospitable to his message. Transjordan was in Herod Antipas\'s territory, not directly under the Jerusalem Sanhedrin\'s jurisdiction.</p>',
    "41": '<p>"Though John never performed a sign, all that John said about this man was true" — the popular verdict draws a deliberate contrast between the Baptist\'s purely verbal witness and Jesus\'s works. John was a trustworthy prophet: his testimony is confirmed by the one he announced. The logic is covenantal: a prophet is validated when his words come true (Deut 18:22). Everything John said about Jesus has been demonstrated; the works are the living verification of the verbal testimony. The Transjordan community receives what Jerusalem rejected.</p>',
    "42": '<p>"And in that place many believed in Jesus" — the brief summary statement closes the section that began at 7:1 with the Sukkot approach and ends here with a retreat and a local harvest. The pattern is consistent throughout the Gospel: institutional Jerusalem resists; peripheral communities receive. Galilee, Samaria, Transjordan — the margins of the Jewish world are where faith takes root, while the center generates rejection. The Evangelist has structured the narrative geographically to make a theological point about where the kingdom arrives.</p>'
  }
}


